334667.log:21:- `TestStartupIdentityWiring`: AST-inspects both `daemon.py` and `cypherclaw_daemon.py` to confirm `bootstrap_identity()` is called before `FirstBootAnnouncer` in `poll_loop()`\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_095247.md:193:└── test_genai.py                   # Test script for generative AI\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_095247.md:657:**Tests:** 141 passing (0.52s)\\\\n+sdp/templates/gemini/verify.md:40:**Verify Agent:** gemini\\\\n+docs/sdp-cli-findings-report.md:226:## Implementation Priority\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:16:### 1.2 Verify DIMM Layout\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:65:**Verify via iDRAC:** Go to **Storage > Controllers** and find the BOSS controller. Confirm:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:74:### 1.6 Verify PERC H755 RAID 5 Array\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:121:Verify by size during the installer. The BOSS drive is ~240GB, the PERC array is ~8.7TB. Hard to mix up.\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:253:Verify you are on the right device:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:347:Verify:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:453:Verify:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:527:With the Performance BIOS profile, the CPU governor should already be set to `performance`. Verify:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:553:Verify XFS is mounted correctly:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:621:The Ollama install script usually creates an `ollama` user. Verify:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:719:Verify both are running:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:727:Test the endpoints:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:736:### 5.6 Verify NUMA Pinning\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:762:### 5.7 Pull a Test Model and Verify\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:779:# Test instance 0\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:782:# Test instance 1\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:940:Verify:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:954:Test connectivity:\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:964:# Test RedisJSON module\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:1031:# Verify it works\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:1040:# Verify the extension loaded\\\\n+docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:1136:### 7.4 Test Inference on Both Sockets\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:133:ADP\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:161:ProjectDocumentation\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3485:| GW-010 | Implement pet-scene generation. Every artwork must feature one or more of CypherClaw's Tamagotchi pets. Scene modes: (a) **Artist attribution** — the pet whose model generated the piece is shown creating/presenting it, (b) **State reflection** — pet's current Tamagotchi state (mood, energy, hunger, stage) determines the scene (tired pet napping, happy pet playing, hungry pet searching for food), (c) **Multi-pet interaction** — collaborative scenes with 2+ pets (teaching, playing, competing, exploring together). The scene mode is varied across generations, with equal probability for each mode. Pet portraits from `pet_sprites.py` should be composited into the Canvas using the DSL's `composite()` method. | MUST | T2 | - Each artwork features at least one pet<br/>- Artist attribution mode: generating model's pet shown<br/>- State reflection mode: current Tamagotchi stats drive scene<br/>- Multi-pet interaction mode: 2+ pets in scene<br/>- Modes distributed roughly equally over time<br/>- Pet sprites from pet_sprites.py used via Canvas.composite()<br/>- Pet stage (Egg through Master) reflected in portrait used |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3486:| GW-011 | Implement Tamagotchi-style animations for Telegram. Animated pieces should be short (3-5 frames), loop-friendly, and evoke the feel of a virtual pet game. Frame transitions should show pet movement, expression changes, or environmental shifts. Use the existing AEAF player (`tools/glyphweave/player.py`) for Telegram message-edit playback at 3000ms minimum frame interval. Also render as animated GIF for the gallery. Animation themes: pet idle animations, pet reactions to events (task complete, evolution, feeding), weather/time-of-day cycles, mini-scenes (pet cooking, coding, stargazing). | SHOULD | T2 | - Animations are 3-5 frames long<br/>- Frame interval >= 3000ms (Telegram rate limit)<br/>- AEAF player used for Telegram display<br/>- Animated GIF generated for gallery<br/>- Pet expression/position changes between frames<br/>- At least 5 distinct animation themes implemented<br/>- Animations feel cohesive (smooth transitions, no jarring jumps) |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3487:| GW-012 | Implement model experiment logging with full telemetry. For every generation attempt, log to PostgreSQL: timestamp, model_id, effort_level, temperature, prompt_text (plan phase + generate phase), raw_llm_output, generated_code, sandbox_execution_time_ms, validation_passes (list of pass/fail per check), retry_count, retry_error_messages, final_art_output, assessment_scores, assessment_model, total_pipeline_time_ms, token_count_estimate, cost_estimate. Provide query functions for the experiment dashboard: per-model aggregates, time-series of scores, comparison matrices. | MUST | T2 | - Every generation attempt logged with all fields<br/>- Failed attempts logged too (for success rate calculation)<br/>- Query by model returns aggregate statistics<br/>- Time-series query returns score progression<br/>- Comparison matrix: model × art_type with avg scores<br/>- Logs queryable from gallery dashboard<br/>- Cost estimates computed from model registry pricing |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3489:| GW-014 | Implement the \\\\\\\"view rendered\\\\\\\" option in Telegram. After sending art as a code block, offer an inline keyboard button \\\\\\\"View Rendered\\\\\\\" that, when pressed, sends the PNG render of the same artwork as a photo message. For animations, offer both \\\\\\\"View Rendered\\\\\\\" (static first frame as PNG) and \\\\\\\"Play Animation\\\\\\\" (triggers AEAF player edit sequence). Also add a \\\\\\\"View in Gallery\\\\\\\" button that links to the artwork's detail page on the gallery website. | SHOULD | T2 | - Text art sent with inline keyboard buttons<br/>- \\\\\\\"View Rendered\\\\\\\" sends PNG as photo reply<br/>- \\\\\\\"Play Animation\\\\\\\" triggers AEAF player for animated pieces<br/>- \\\\\\\"View in Gallery\\\\\\\" links to gallery detail URL<br/>- Buttons only appear on art messages, not all messages<br/>- Callback query handlers registered in daemon |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3495:| GW-020 | Copy the GlyphWeave foundations research document to the server at `/home/user/cypherclaw/docs/glyphweave-foundations.md`. This document should be included (or summarized) in generation prompts so the LLM understands the art form's history, principles, and constraints. The art engine should reference specific principles from the foundations when constructing prompts — e.g., citing the \\\\\\\"Structure = Content\\\\\\\" principle from concrete poetry, or the Paul Smith constraint-based creativity lesson. | MUST | T1 | - Foundations document present on server at specified path<br/>- Art prompts reference specific principles from the document<br/>- At least 3 principles cited in generation prompts<br/>- Document accessible to all generation processes |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3497:## Implementation Phases\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3503:Build the art engine, validator, prompt templates, and PNG renderer. This is the core creation pipeline. Test with manual invocation.\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3796:| GW-010 | Implement pet-scene generation. Every artwork must feature one or more of CypherClaw's Tamagotchi pets. Scene modes: (a) **Artist attribution** — the pet whose model generated the piece is shown creating/presenting it, (b) **State reflection** — pet's current Tamagotchi state (mood, energy, hunger, stage) determines the scene (tired pet napping, happy pet playing, hungry pet searching for food), (c) **Multi-pet interaction** — collaborative scenes with 2+ pets (teaching, playing, competing, exploring together). The scene mode is varied across generations, with equal probability for each mode. Pet portraits from `pet_sprites.py` should be composited into the Canvas using the DSL's `composite()` method. | MUST | T2 | - Each artwork features at least one pet<br/>- Artist attribution mode: generating model's pet shown<br/>- State reflection mode: current Tamagotchi stats drive scene<br/>- Multi-pet interaction mode: 2+ pets in scene<br/>- Modes distributed roughly equally over time<br/>- Pet sprites from pet_sprites.py used via Canvas.composite()<br/>- Pet stage (Egg through Master) reflected in portrait used |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3797:| GW-011 | Implement Tamagotchi-style animations for Telegram. Animated pieces should be short (3-5 frames), loop-friendly, and evoke the feel of a virtual pet game. Frame transitions should show pet movement, expression changes, or environmental shifts. Use the existing AEAF player (`tools/glyphweave/player.py`) for Telegram message-edit playback at 3000ms minimum frame interval. Also render as animated GIF for the gallery. Animation themes: pet idle animations, pet reactions to events (task complete, evolution, feeding), weather/time-of-day cycles, mini-scenes (pet cooking, coding, stargazing). | SHOULD | T2 | - Animations are 3-5 frames long<br/>- Frame interval >= 3000ms (Telegram rate limit)<br/>- AEAF player used for Telegram display<br/>- Animated GIF generated for gallery<br/>- Pet expression/position changes between frames<br/>- At least 5 distinct animation themes implemented<br/>- Animations feel cohesive (smooth transitions, no jarring jumps) |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3798:| GW-012 | Implement model experiment logging with full telemetry. For every generation attempt, log to PostgreSQL: timestamp, model_id, effort_level, temperature, prompt_text (plan phase + generate phase), raw_llm_output, generated_code, sandbox_execution_time_ms, validation_passes (list of pass/fail per check), retry_count, retry_error_messages, final_art_output, assessment_scores, assessment_model, total_pipeline_time_ms, token_count_estimate, cost_estimate. Provide query functions for the experiment dashboard: per-model aggregates, time-series of scores, comparison matrices. | MUST | T2 | - Every generation attempt logged with all fields<br/>- Failed attempts logged too (for success rate calculation)<br/>- Query by model returns aggregate statistics<br/>- Time-series query returns score progression<br/>- Comparison matrix: model × art_type with avg scores<br/>- Logs queryable from gallery dashboard<br/>- Cost estimates computed from model registry pricing |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3800:| GW-014 | Implement the \\\\\\\"view rendered\\\\\\\" option in Telegram. After sending art as a code block, offer an inline keyboard button \\\\\\\"View Rendered\\\\\\\" that, when pressed, sends the PNG render of the same artwork as a photo message. For animations, offer both \\\\\\\"View Rendered\\\\\\\" (static first frame as PNG) and \\\\\\\"Play Animation\\\\\\\" (triggers AEAF player edit sequence). Also add a \\\\\\\"View in Gallery\\\\\\\" button that links to the artwork's detail page on the gallery website. | SHOULD | T2 | - Text art sent with inline keyboard buttons<br/>- \\\\\\\"View Rendered\\\\\\\" sends PNG as photo reply<br/>- \\\\\\\"Play Animation\\\\\\\" triggers AEAF player for animated pieces<br/>- \\\\\\\"View in Gallery\\\\\\\" links to gallery detail URL<br/>- Buttons only appear on art messages, not all messages<br/>- Callback query handlers registered in daemon |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3806:| GW-020 | Copy the GlyphWeave foundations research document to the server at `/home/user/cypherclaw/docs/glyphweave-foundations.md`. This document should be included (or summarized) in generation prompts so the LLM understands the art form's history, principles, and constraints. The art engine should reference specific principles from the foundations when constructing prompts — e.g., citing the \\\\\\\"Structure = Content\\\\\\\" principle from concrete poetry, or the Paul Smith constraint-based creativity lesson. | MUST | T1 | - Foundations document present on server at specified path<br/>- Art prompts reference specific principles from the document<br/>- At least 3 principles cited in generation prompts<br/>- Document accessible to all generation processes |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3808:## Implementation Phases\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3814:Build the art engine, validator, prompt templates, and PNG renderer. This is the core creation pipeline. Test with manual invocation.\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:4112:| GW-010 | Implement pet-scene generation. Every artwork must feature one or more of CypherClaw's Tamagotchi pets. Scene modes: (a) **Artist attribution** — the pet whose model generated the piece is shown creating/presenting it, (b) **State reflection** — pet's current Tamagotchi state (mood, energy, hunger, stage) determines the scene (tired pet napping, happy pet playing, hungry pet searching for food), (c) **Multi-pet interaction** — collaborative scenes with 2+ pets (teaching, playing, competing, exploring together). The scene mode is varied across generations, with equal probability for each mode. Pet portraits from `pet_sprites.py` should be composited into the Canvas using the DSL's `composite()` method. | MUST | T2 | - Each artwork features at least one pet<br/>- Artist attribution mode: generating model's pet shown<br/>- State reflection mode: current Tamagotchi stats drive scene<br/>- Multi-pet interaction mode: 2+ pets in scene<br/>- Modes distributed roughly equally over time<br/>- Pet sprites from pet_sprites.py used via Canvas.composite()<br/>- Pet stage (Egg through Master) reflected in portrait used |\\\\n+docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:4113:| G