docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:5:**Context:** CypherClaw evolves from a headless generative art server into an embodied, interactive organism with a face, a voice, and the ability to collaborate with humans in real time.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:15:When a human sits down in front of it, the creature doesn't stop what it's doing. It keeps breathing through its 30-minute narrative cycle. But it *notices* the human. It responds. The human plays a MIDI keyboard and hears the system answer through the Theramini. The human types on a mechanical keyboard and watches their words bloom across the face. The gallery ripples with the weight of all these inputs at once — every sensor, every voice, every heartbeat of the machine rendered as living ASCII and emoji.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:25:- **Gallery Monitor:** Widescreen 4K display. Wall-mounted via monitor arm. Displays the expansive GlyphWeave canvas — the full generative art output shaped by all sensory voices simultaneously. Gallery-quality presentation.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:30:- **Front-Facing Camera Mic — The Witness:** Built into the camera mounted on/near the face monitor. Captures intimate close-range audio — the user's breath, keystrokes, murmured words. The closest sensory voice to the human.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:42:- **Speaker:** Room-filling audio output. Soft, ambient, spacey. The system's voice.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:50:## Sensory Voice Architecture (SenseWeave v2)
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:54:All sensory voices are equal participants. No hierarchy. The system must support hot-pluggable sensors — add a new mic, camera, or USB device and it integrates automatically without breaking the system. Remove a sensor and the system gracefully adapts.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:56:### The Nine Voices
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:58:| Voice | Hardware | Data Type | Update Frequency |
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:70:**Additionally:** The mechanical typewriter keyboard feeds into the narrative engine as semantic input AND registers as sensory data (rhythm, speed, pauses). It may or may not warrant its own named voice — perhaps **The Scribe**.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:74:When multiple senses confirm the same event (e.g., the Theramini detects proximity while The Eye sees a hand, while The Witness hears a voice), the system renders with increased boldness and intensity. This existing principle extends to all nine voices.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:90:When a human sits down at the keyboards, the system doesn't pause its cycle. Instead, human input becomes additional sensory voices layered on top of the autonomous arc. The system gives *immediate positive feedback*:
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:97:Soft, spacey, ethereal. Reference artists: Simon Posford (ambient/downtempo work), Gom, early Arca. Avoid sharp sounds. The Theramini is the primary voice. The system can sample and process audio from any input to create generative soundscapes. Everything breathes.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:133:- **SenseWeave:** Needs v2 with plugin architecture, new sensor voices, and hot-plug support.
docs/20260402-cypherclaw-embodiment-research-brief.md:136:- **Theramini Integration:** Becomes the primary audio feedback voice in performance mode. The existing planned feedback loop (MIDI → Theramini → audio → analysis → new generation) is now critical path.
